-----------------------------------------
------+++ Root: Ullman (7)

Computer scientists should really refer to their Ullman number. Mine is 5. This is the first Erdos
link that I found quite quickly with the help of DBLP.

According to the [[http://personalwebs.oakland.edu/~grossman/Erdos2][Erdos2]] list

	* Erdös (0)
	* Ronald L. Graham (1)
	* [[http://136.199.54.185/%7Eley/db/indices/a-tree/u/Ullman%3AJeffrey_D=.html][Jeffrey D. Ullman]] (2)

According to DBLP

	* [[http://136.199.54.185/%7Eley/db/indices/a-tree/s/Sethi%3ARavi.html][Ravi Sethi]] (3)
	* [[http://136.199.54.185/%7Eley/db/indices/a-tree/m/MacQueen%3ADavid_B=.html][David MacQueen]] (4)
	* [[http://136.199.54.185/%7Eley/db/indices/a-tree/a/Appel%3AAndrew_W=.html][Andrew Appel]] (5)
	* [[http://136.199.54.185/%7Eley/db/indices/a-tree/t/Tolmach%3AAndrew_P=.html][Andrew Tolmach]] (6)
	* [[http://136.199.54.185/%7Eley/db/indices/a-tree/v/Visser%3aEelco.html][Eelco Visser]] (7)

-----------------------------------------
-------+++ Root: Salomaa

Another path might exist through [[http://www.informatik.uni-trier.de/~ley/db/indices/a-tree/s/Salomaa%3AArto.html][Arto Salomaa]] (2) but I haven't found it yet.

-----------------------------------------
-------+++ Conclusion

(1) The length 6 and 7 paths are completely disjoint and correspond to algebraic and strategic periods, respectively.

(2) It is surprising (or maybe not) how people with offices next to each other don't write papers together. Should do that more often.

-- Main.EelcoVisser - 16 Mar 2004
